{head1}My Journey with Custom Markup Languages{.head1}

{para}Published on: March 15, 2024 | By: RML Developer{.para}

{head2}Introduction{.head2}

{para}Today I want to share my experience creating {bold}RML (RazzMarkupLanguage){.bold}, a custom markup language that makes writing structured content more intuitive and fun.{.para}

{quote}
"The best tools are the ones that feel natural to use, almost like they're an extension of your own thoughts."
{.quote}

{head2}Why Create Another Markup Language?{.head2}

{para}You might wonder: "Why create another markup language when we already have HTML, Markdown, and others?" Here are my reasons:{.para}

{list}
    {listitem}{bold}Intuitive Syntax:{.bold} The curly brace notation feels more natural than angle brackets{.listitem}
    {listitem}{bold}Clear Closing Tags:{.bold} The dot notation makes it obvious where tags end{.listitem}
    {listitem}{bold}Easy to Learn:{.bold} Simple rules that anyone can pick up quickly{.listitem}
    {listitem}{bold}Powerful Features:{.bold} All the functionality of HTML with simpler syntax{.listitem}
{.list}

{head2}The Technical Journey{.head2}

{para}Building RML involved several key components:{.para}

{head3}1. The Parser{.head3}

{para}The heart of RML is its parser, written in JavaScript. It uses regular expressions to identify RML patterns and convert them to HTML:{.para}

{para}Example transformation: {code}{head1}Title{.head1}{.code} becomes {code}<h1>Title</h1>{.code}{.para}

{head3}2. Chrome Extension{.head3}

{para}To make RML accessible, I created a Chrome extension that:{.para}

{orderedlist}
    {listitem}Detects .rml files automatically{.listitem}
    {listitem}Parses RML content in real-time{.listitem}
    {listitem}Applies beautiful default styling{.listitem}
    {listitem}Provides a user-friendly interface{.listitem}
{.orderedlist}

